# Mobile QA with Maestro

This skill drives a React Native / Expo app on the iOS Simulator (and, where
trivial, the Android emulator) the way a human tester would: it looks at the
screen, decides what to do, taps and types through real UI, and asserts on the
result. The agent never reaches into app internals — there is no SwiftUI state
to introspect in a React Native app, so everything happens through the
accessibility tree and visible text.

The loop is **hybrid**: prefer the cheap `inspect_screen` (a compact
accessibility-tree JSON) to decide what is on screen; fall back to
`take_screenshot` (vision) only when layout, color, or visual correctness is
what you are judging. Then `run` an action and re-observe. Capture screenshots
as evidence at every assertion.

## Why Maestro (and not the SwiftUI approach)

The gstack `/ios-qa` skill introspects `@Observable` SwiftUI state over an
embedded HTTP bridge. A React Native app has no such state to read, so this
skill automates through the **accessibility tree / visible text** instead.
Maestro drives the iOS Simulator through its OWN bundled XCUITest driver — not
idb, not Appium/WebDriverAgent — and is cross-platform, so the same flows run on
the Android emulator with no rewrite.

## Driver tooling: who does what

- **Maestro** is the driver. It taps, types, swipes, scrolls, and asserts. The
  agent talks to it through the official Maestro **MCP server**, which exposes a
  PERSISTENT session with three tools:
  - `mcp__maestro__inspect_screen` — compact accessibility-tree JSON. Cheap.
    Prefer this to decide. (Referred to below as `inspect_screen`.)
  - `mcp__maestro__take_screenshot` — a PNG for vision. Use when layout / visual
    correctness matters. (Referred to below as `take_screenshot`.)
  - `mcp__maestro__run` — execute an inline YAML flow:
    `tapOn:` / `inputText:` / `swipe:` / `scroll:` / `doubleTapOn:` /
    `assertVisible:` and friends. (Referred to below as `run`.)
- **`simctl`** (`xcrun simctl`) is a UTILITY, not a driver. It CANNOT tap or
  type. Use it to boot/install/launch/terminate, take a raw screenshot
  (`xcrun simctl io booted screenshot <path>`), seed the photo/media library
  (`xcrun simctl addmedia booted <files...>`), pre-grant or revoke permissions
  (`xcrun simctl privacy booted grant|revoke <service> <bundle-id>`), and open
  deep links (`xcrun simctl openurl booted <url>`).
- **Android equivalents** (where you run there): input is built into `adb` — no
  companion driver needed. `adb shell input tap <x> <y>` /
  `adb shell input text <s>`, emulator control via `adb emu ...`, permissions
  via `adb shell pm grant <pkg> <permission>`.

## Targeting elements

Target by **visible text by default** — `tapOn: "Login"` — so flows work on
uninstrumented apps. When a stable identifier exists, prefer
`tapOn: { id: "login-button" }` (Maestro `id:` maps to React Native `testID` /
`accessibilityIdentifier`) or the accessibility label, because it survives copy
changes. Fall back to text when no stable id is present.

**OS permission alerts** (photos, camera, notifications, tracking) are handled
by tapping the system button's TEXT through Maestro — e.g.
`run` → `tapOn: "Allow Full Access"`, `tapOn: "Don't Allow"`,
`tapOn: "Allow While Using App"`. You can also pre-grant or pre-deny with
`simctl privacy` in Phase 0 to skip or to deterministically test the flow.

## Prerequisites (install once)

- macOS with Xcode + at least one iOS Simulator runtime installed.
- Node + the repo's package manager (detect: `pnpm` / `npm` / `yarn` / `bun`
  from the lockfile).
- A Java runtime (JDK 11+) — Maestro requires it. On hosts where shell state
  does not persist between commands, prepend the maestro bin dir to `PATH` on
  each invocation: `export PATH="$HOME/.maestro/bin:$PATH"`.
- **Maestro:**
  ```bash
  curl -fsSL "https://get.maestro.mobile.dev" | bash
  # or: brew tap mobile-dev-inc/tap && brew install mobile-dev-inc/tap/maestro
  maestro --version
  ```
- **Maestro MCP server**, registered with your agent host:
  ```bash
  claude mcp add maestro -- maestro mcp
  ```
  Confirm the three tools (`inspect_screen`, `take_screenshot`, `run`) are
  available before a full run.

## Phase 0: Environment setup & discovery

Everything in this phase is **discovered from the repo** — never hardcode a
bundle id, scheme, run command, or simulator name.

1. **Maestro + MCP present.** `maestro --version` succeeds; the Maestro MCP
   tools are listed. If not, run the install + `claude mcp add maestro` steps
   above.

2. **Detect the iOS bundle id and URL scheme.** Expo managed apps declare these
   in `app.json` or `app.config.{js,ts}`:
   ```bash
   # Static app.json:
   cat app.json | python3 -c 'import json,sys;d=json.load(sys.stdin)["expo"];print("bundleId:",d.get("ios",{}).get("bundleIdentifier"));print("scheme:",d.get("scheme"))'
   # Or grep when config is dynamic / TS:
   grep -RnoE 'bundleIdentifier"?\s*[:=]\s*"[^"]+"' app.json app.config.* 2>/dev/null
   grep -RnoE '\bscheme"?\s*[:=]\s*"[^"]+"' app.json app.config.* 2>/dev/null
   ```
   If the app is already prebuilt, read it from native:
   `grep -RnoE 'PRODUCT_BUNDLE_IDENTIFIER = [^;]+' ios/*.xcodeproj/project.pbxproj`.

3. **Detect the run command.** Prefer a repo dev script that ALSO starts backend
   services, so network calls work during QA:
   ```bash
   # Look for a wrapper script that boots backend + app (e.g. "dev", "start", "run:ios", a Makefile target, a scripts/ entry):
   ls scripts 2>/dev/null; ls -1 | grep -iE 'dev|start|run' 2>/dev/null
   # Inspect package.json scripts:
   cat package.json | python3 -c 'import json,sys;print("\n".join(f"{k}: {v}" for k,v in json.load(sys.stdin).get("scripts",{}).items()))'
   ```
   If such a script exists, prefer it. Otherwise fall back to the Expo native
   build, which does a prebuild + pod install on first run (slow — minutes):
   ```bash
   npx expo run:ios          # add --device "<Simulator Name>" to target a specific sim
   ```
   Detect the package manager from the lockfile (`pnpm-lock.yaml`,
   `package-lock.json`, `yarn.lock`, `bun.lockb`) and use it consistently.

4. **Boot a simulator — recent, not bleeding-edge.** The newest Xcode/runtime
   combinations can be flaky for driver attach. Prefer a runtime one major
   version behind the latest installed.
   ```bash
   xcrun simctl list devices available
   xcrun simctl boot "<UDID-or-name>" 2>/dev/null || true
   open -a Simulator
   ```

5. **Build + launch the app** via the detected command (dev script preferred,
   else `npx expo run:ios`). Confirm it reaches the first screen.

   An `expo-dev-client` build often opens with the **Expo dev-menu** overlay
   (and/or a floating "Tools" bubble) covering the first screen, so an immediate
   assert against app content fails. Dismiss the dev-menu FIRST — tap the close
   control ("Close" / the `xmark` icon), NOT "Continue" — then `take_screenshot`
   to confirm the real app UI is visible. Make the taps OPTIONAL so an absent
   menu doesn't fail the flow:
   ```yaml
   # Expo dev-client may open over the app with a dev-menu / "Tools" bubble.
   # Dismiss it FIRST (tap Close / the xmark — NOT "Continue"); optional so an
   # absent menu doesn't fail the flow.
   - tapOn:
       text: "Close"
       optional: true
   - tapOn:
       id: "xmark"
       optional: true
   ```

6. **Seed media / pre-grant permissions as the flows need.** For a media app,
   seed the photo library and pre-grant so the app has something to show:
   ```bash
   xcrun simctl addmedia booted ~/path/to/sample1.jpg ~/path/to/sample2.heic
   xcrun simctl privacy booted grant photos <bundle-id>
   ```
   To test a permission FLOW instead, revoke first
   (`xcrun simctl privacy booted revoke photos <bundle-id>`) and drive the
   system alert via Maestro in Phase 2.

7. **Smoke-test the Maestro ↔ simulator connection once** before a full run —
   one `inspect_screen` (or a trivial `run` with a single `assertVisible:` for a
   known label). If the driver fails to attach, switch to a less bleeding-edge
   iOS runtime and retry before proceeding.

## Phase 1: Derive the QA plan

1. **If the repo has a QA spec, follow it.** Look for a `QA/` directory, a
   `QA.md`, or per-flow QA docs:
   ```bash
   ls QA 2>/dev/null; find . -maxdepth 3 -iname 'QA*.md' -not -path '*/node_modules/*' 2>/dev/null
   ```
   Read it and turn each documented flow into a concrete checklist.

2. **Otherwise, QA the changed surface.** Discover what changed and scope the
   plan to the screens those files render:
   ```bash
   git diff --name-only "$(git merge-base HEAD origin/main 2>/dev/null || echo HEAD~1)"...HEAD
   ```
   Map changed components/screens to the user-facing flows that exercise them.

3. **Produce a concrete per-flow plan** — one entry per flow with: entry point,
   the exact taps/inputs, and the assertion that proves it works. Show the user
   the plan before executing a long run.

## Phase 2: Execute the loop (one flow at a time)

For each flow, iterate:

1. **Observe.** `inspect_screen` to read the accessibility tree (cheap,
   preferred). Use `take_screenshot` instead when you are judging layout, color,
   spacing, or visual correctness. On the FIRST observation after launch,
   dismiss any lingering Expo dev-menu / "Tools" bubble before asserting — an
   optional `tapOn` for "Close" / the `xmark` icon (see Phase 0), then a
   screenshot to confirm the real app UI is visible.
2. **Decide.** Compare what's on screen against the flow's next step.
3. **Act.** `run` an inline YAML action — e.g.
   `run` → `tapOn: "Continue"`, `inputText: "test@example.com"`,
   `swipe: { direction: UP }`, `scroll`, `doubleTapOn: { id: "photo-3" }`.
   Handle any OS permission alert by tapping its button text.
4. **Re-observe & assert.** `inspect_screen` again, or `run` →
   `assertVisible: "Welcome"` (or `assertVisible: { id: "home-feed" }`). Capture
   a screenshot as evidence — either `take_screenshot` or
   `xcrun simctl io booted screenshot <path>`.
5. **Record** pass/fail for the flow with the evidence screenshot and a one-line
   note on what was verified. On failure, capture the failing screen + the
   accessibility tree so a fixer can reproduce it.

Drive every action through visible UI. Do not skip steps by relaunching to a
deep link unless the flow's entry point IS a deep link
(`xcrun simctl openurl booted <url>`).

## Phase 3: Report & (optionally) hand off

1. **Report** a per-flow pass/fail table, each row linking its evidence
   screenshot and a one-line note. Lead with the failures.
2. For each failure, include: the flow, the step that broke, the visible
   symptom, the screenshot, and the accessibility-tree node if relevant.
3. **Optionally hand failures to a fixer.** If the user wants bugs fixed, pass
   each failing flow (with repro steps + evidence) to your code-fixing flow:
   reproduce on the simulator, locate the root cause in the RN source, apply a
   minimal fix, rebuild, and re-run the SAME Maestro flow to confirm the fix.

## Fallback drivers (only if Maestro can't attach)

- **Appium + XCUITest.** Also taps by text via an `-ios predicate string`.
  ```bash
  npm i -g appium && appium driver install xcuitest
  ```
  Heavier setup (WebDriverAgent build, capabilities) — use only if Maestro's
  bundled driver won't attach to your runtime.
- **idb** — last resort only. Its Homebrew bottle is a stale 2022 build and is
  frequently broken on current macOS/Xcode; reach for it only when nothing else
  works.

## Failure modes + recovery

| Symptom | Likely cause | Action |
|---|---|---|
| Maestro can't attach to the simulator | bleeding-edge iOS runtime | Boot a runtime one major behind; re-run the Phase 0 smoke test |
| First assertion fails immediately after launch | Expo dev-menu / "Tools" bubble overlaying the app | Dismiss it first with an optional `tapOn` Close / `xmark` (NOT "Continue"), then screenshot to confirm |
| `tapOn: "<text>"` finds nothing | text differs from what's rendered | `inspect_screen` to read the real labels; target by `id:` if present |
| App shows empty media / no photos | library not seeded | `xcrun simctl addmedia booted <files>` then relaunch |
| Permission alert blocks the flow | service not pre-granted | Tap the system button text via `run`, or pre-grant with `simctl privacy` |
| Network calls fail / backend down | ran bare `expo run:ios`, no services | Use the repo's dev script that also starts backend services |
| `expo run:ios` very slow on first run | prebuild + pod install | Expected once; subsequent launches are fast |
| MCP tools missing | server not registered | `claude mcp add maestro -- maestro mcp`; restart the session |
